/* CISA :: content/quiz3.js — CISA Domain 3 question bank (100 items). */
window.CISA = window.CISA || {}; CISA.questions = CISA.questions || [];
CISA.questions.push.apply(CISA.questions, [
{"id":"D3-001","domain":3,"obj":"3A1","diff":"easy","q":"An IS auditor is reviewing a large system-development project. Which body is PRIMARILY responsible for approving the project charter, allocating funding, and resolving cross-departmental conflicts?","options":["The project manager","The quality assurance team","The project steering committee","The systems development team"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>The project steering committee</strong> — the steering committee provides senior-management oversight, approves the charter and budget, and adjudicates conflicts that cross departmental lines, giving the project business direction and authority.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The project manager</b>: manages day-to-day execution, schedule and resources but does not hold the authority to approve funding or arbitrate senior cross-departmental disputes.</span><span class='qd'><b>The quality assurance team</b>: verifies that deliverables meet standards; it has no governance or funding-approval mandate.</span><span class='qd'><b>The systems development team</b>: builds the solution and has no authority over project funding or charter approval.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-002","domain":3,"obj":"3A2","diff":"easy","q":"During a project review, an IS auditor wants to determine whether a proposed system was economically justified before development began. Which document should the auditor examine FIRST?","options":["The system design specification","The business case","The user acceptance test plan","The data conversion plan"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>The business case</strong> — the business case documents the expected costs, benefits, and strategic alignment that justify the investment, so it is the primary evidence of economic justification and should be reviewed first.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The system design specification</b>: describes how the solution will be built, not whether it was economically justified.</span><span class='qd'><b>The user acceptance test plan</b>: addresses whether the delivered system meets requirements, produced much later than the justification decision.</span><span class='qd'><b>The data conversion plan</b>: governs migration of legacy data and has nothing to do with the initial economic justification.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-003","domain":3,"obj":"3A3","diff":"hard","q":"An IS auditor notes that a project team delivered the full system in a single, sequential pass with clearly defined phases and formal sign-offs between each. Which development methodology BEST describes this approach?","options":["Waterfall","Agile (Scrum)","DevOps","Prototyping"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Waterfall</strong> — the waterfall model progresses through sequential, well-defined phases (requirements, design, build, test, implement) with formal approvals gating each transition, exactly as described.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Agile (Scrum)</b>: delivers working increments iteratively in short sprints rather than one sequential pass with phase gates.</span><span class='qd'><b>DevOps</b>: emphasizes continuous integration and delivery with automated pipelines, not a single sequential build.</span><span class='qd'><b>Prototyping</b>: builds successive throwaway or evolutionary models to refine requirements, not a single gated pass.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-004","domain":3,"obj":"3A4","diff":"easy","q":"An IS auditor is evaluating input controls for a payroll application. Which control BEST ensures that a keyed employee number was not mistyped?","options":["A batch total of gross pay","A check digit on the employee number","An output distribution log","A run-to-run control total"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>A check digit on the employee number</strong> — a check digit is an extra digit computed from the other digits so that a single transposition or transcription error in the key field is detected at input, preventing posting to the wrong record.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A batch total of gross pay</b>: reconciles monetary amounts across a batch but does not validate the correctness of an individual key field.</span><span class='qd'><b>An output distribution log</b>: controls who receives reports after processing, not the accuracy of an input field.</span><span class='qd'><b>A run-to-run control total</b>: verifies completeness between processing stages, not the correctness of a keyed identifier.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-005","domain":3,"obj":"3B1","diff":"hard","q":"An IS auditor is reviewing testing for a new order-entry system. Which test is PRIMARILY intended to confirm that the business users agree the system meets their requirements before go-live?","options":["Unit testing","User acceptance testing","Integration testing","Regression testing"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>User acceptance testing</strong> — UAT is performed by end users against business requirements to confirm the system is fit for purpose and to authorize go-live, making it the decisive requirements-conformance test from the business perspective.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Unit testing</b>: verifies individual program modules in isolation and is a developer activity, not business sign-off.</span><span class='qd'><b>Integration testing</b>: confirms that modules work together correctly, not that users accept the system.</span><span class='qd'><b>Regression testing</b>: confirms that changes did not break existing functionality, not overall business acceptance.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-006","domain":3,"obj":"3B2","diff":"easy","q":"An IS auditor finds that emergency changes are routinely applied directly to production without approval, then documented afterward. What is the auditor's GREATEST concern?","options":["Emergency changes take longer to deploy","Developers dislike the paperwork","The change log grows too large","Unauthorized or untested changes may remain in production"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Unauthorized or untested changes may remain in production</strong> — retroactive documentation without a control to force timely review means changes that were never properly authorized or tested can persist, undermining integrity and availability, which is the core risk.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Emergency changes take longer to deploy</b>: emergency processes are typically faster, and speed is not the control concern.</span><span class='qd'><b>Developers dislike the paperwork</b>: staff preference is not an audit risk.</span><span class='qd'><b>The change log grows too large</b>: log size is a housekeeping issue, not a control weakness.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-007","domain":3,"obj":"3B3","diff":"easy","q":"Before a data conversion from a legacy system, an IS auditor wants assurance that all records will be carried over completely and accurately. Which control provides the BEST such assurance?","options":["Reconciliation of record counts and control totals before and after conversion","A signed data-conversion policy","Encrypting the legacy database backup","Training users on the new system"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Reconciliation of record counts and control totals before and after conversion</strong> — comparing counts and financial/hash totals of source and target data directly demonstrates that records were migrated completely and accurately, the fundamental conversion control.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A signed data-conversion policy</b>: sets expectations but does not prove the actual conversion was complete and accurate.</span><span class='qd'><b>Encrypting the legacy database backup</b>: protects confidentiality of the backup, not conversion accuracy or completeness.</span><span class='qd'><b>Training users on the new system</b>: improves adoption but provides no assurance over converted data.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-008","domain":3,"obj":"3B4","diff":"easy","q":"An IS auditor is asked to evaluate whether a recently implemented system delivered the benefits promised in its business case. Which activity is BEST suited to this objective?","options":["A feasibility study","A unit test","A post-implementation review","A code walkthrough"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>A post-implementation review</strong> — a PIR is conducted after the system stabilizes to compare realized benefits, costs, and performance against the original business case, directly answering whether promised benefits were achieved.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A feasibility study</b>: is performed before development to assess viability, not after implementation to measure benefits.</span><span class='qd'><b>A unit test</b>: checks a single module's correctness, unrelated to benefit realization.</span><span class='qd'><b>A code walkthrough</b>: reviews source code quality, not delivered business value.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-009","domain":3,"obj":"3A1","diff":"easy","q":"An IS auditor reviews a project schedule and wants to identify the sequence of activities that determines the minimum possible project duration. Which technique provides this?","options":["Function point analysis","Critical path method","Earned value analysis","Rapid application development"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Critical path method</strong> — CPM identifies the longest chain of dependent activities with zero slack, which sets the shortest time in which the project can finish; any delay on this path delays the whole project.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Function point analysis</b>: sizes software functionality for estimation, not the schedule's critical sequence.</span><span class='qd'><b>Earned value analysis</b>: measures cost and schedule performance against plan, not which activities define minimum duration.</span><span class='qd'><b>Rapid application development</b>: is a development methodology, not a scheduling technique.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-010","domain":3,"obj":"3A2","diff":"hard","q":"An IS auditor reviews a feasibility study that concluded a project was viable. Which type of feasibility is PRIMARILY concerned with whether the organization has the skills, culture, and willingness to operate the new system?","options":["Operational feasibility","Technical feasibility","Economic feasibility","Legal feasibility"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Operational feasibility</strong> — operational feasibility assesses whether the organization's people, processes, culture, and skills can actually run and sustain the solution once delivered, which is the human/organizational dimension described.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Technical feasibility</b>: examines whether the technology and infrastructure can deliver the solution, not organizational readiness.</span><span class='qd'><b>Economic feasibility</b>: weighs costs against benefits, not skills or willingness.</span><span class='qd'><b>Legal feasibility</b>: checks compliance with laws and contracts, not operational capacity.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-011","domain":3,"obj":"3A3","diff":"easy","q":"In an agile project, an IS auditor observes that requirements evolve each sprint and working software is delivered every two weeks. Which control should the auditor expect to compensate for the lack of comprehensive up-front documentation?","options":["A frozen requirements baseline","A single big-bang release at project end","Elimination of user involvement","A well-maintained and prioritized product backlog"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>A well-maintained and prioritized product backlog</strong> — in agile, the product backlog is the authoritative, continuously groomed record of requirements and priorities, providing traceability and control in place of heavy up-front documentation.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A frozen requirements baseline</b>: contradicts agile's embrace of change and is not how agile controls scope.</span><span class='qd'><b>A single big-bang release at project end</b>: is the opposite of agile's incremental delivery.</span><span class='qd'><b>Elimination of user involvement</b>: agile depends on continuous user collaboration, not its removal.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-012","domain":3,"obj":"3A4","diff":"easy","q":"An IS auditor is assessing processing controls in a billing system. Which control BEST detects that a transaction was lost or added between two processing runs?","options":["Reasonableness check","Field format validation","Run-to-run control totals","Sequence checking of input"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Run-to-run control totals</strong> — carrying totals forward and reconciling them from one processing stage to the next detects any records lost, duplicated, or added during processing, addressing completeness across runs.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Reasonableness check</b>: flags values outside expected ranges but does not detect lost or added records between runs.</span><span class='qd'><b>Field format validation</b>: verifies that data conforms to a format at input, not completeness across processing.</span><span class='qd'><b>Sequence checking of input</b>: detects gaps in input numbering but not records lost between internal processing runs.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-013","domain":3,"obj":"3B1","diff":"hard","q":"An IS auditor reviews the test strategy for a payroll replacement. Old and new systems will process the same live data in parallel and their outputs compared for one pay cycle. Which testing approach is this, and what is its PRIMARY benefit?","options":["Pilot testing; limits exposure to one location","Regression testing; confirms old features still work","Parallel testing; validates new results against a proven baseline","Stress testing; confirms performance under load"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Parallel testing; validates new results against a proven baseline</strong> — running both systems on the same data and comparing outputs lets the team confirm the new system produces results matching the trusted legacy system before cutover, its main benefit.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Pilot testing; limits exposure to one location</b>: pilot deploys to a subset of users, not both systems on identical data.</span><span class='qd'><b>Regression testing; confirms old features still work</b>: regression re-tests changed software, not two systems in parallel.</span><span class='qd'><b>Stress testing; confirms performance under load</b>: stress testing pushes volume limits, not output comparison.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-014","domain":3,"obj":"3B2","diff":"easy","q":"An IS auditor examines a release management process. Which practice BEST reduces the risk that untested code reaches production?","options":["Granting developers direct write access to production","Storing source code only on developer laptops","Allowing developers to migrate their own code to production","Separation of development, test, and production environments"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Separation of development, test, and production environments</strong> — segregating environments ensures code is promoted through controlled stages and independently verified before production, preventing untested or unauthorized code from reaching live systems.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Granting developers direct write access to production</b>: removes the very control needed and increases the risk it is meant to prevent.</span><span class='qd'><b>Storing source code only on developer laptops</b>: creates loss and integrity risks and no promotion control.</span><span class='qd'><b>Allowing developers to migrate their own code to production</b>: violates segregation of duties and enables untested changes to go live.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-015","domain":3,"obj":"3B3","diff":"easy","q":"During a system migration, an IS auditor wants assurance that sensitive customer data was not exposed while being transferred to the new platform. Which control is MOST relevant?","options":["Record-count reconciliation","Encryption of data in transit during migration","User acceptance testing","Function point analysis"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Encryption of data in transit during migration</strong> — encrypting the data as it moves protects confidentiality against interception during the transfer, directly addressing the exposure concern.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Record-count reconciliation</b>: assures completeness of migration, not confidentiality of the data.</span><span class='qd'><b>User acceptance testing</b>: confirms functional fitness, not protection of data in transit.</span><span class='qd'><b>Function point analysis</b>: is an estimation technique, unrelated to migration security.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-016","domain":3,"obj":"3B4","diff":"easy","q":"A post-implementation review of a new CRM reveals that projected productivity gains did not materialize. What should the IS auditor recommend the organization do FIRST?","options":["Immediately decommission the CRM","Replace the project manager","Extend the warranty period","Determine the root cause of the shortfall before acting"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Determine the root cause of the shortfall before acting</strong> — understanding why benefits were not realized (adoption, process, data, or estimation issues) is essential before any corrective decision, so root-cause analysis comes first.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Immediately decommission the CRM</b>: is premature and could destroy value before the cause is known.</span><span class='qd'><b>Replace the project manager</b>: assigns blame without evidence and does not address the underlying issue.</span><span class='qd'><b>Extend the warranty period</b>: does nothing to explain or fix the benefit shortfall.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-017","domain":3,"obj":"3A1","diff":"easy","q":"An IS auditor is reviewing project governance. The clearest evidence that a project remains aligned with its approved objectives and budget would be found in:","options":["The programmer's personal notebook","Vendor marketing brochures","Regular steering committee minutes and status reports","The office seating chart"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Regular steering committee minutes and status reports</strong> — these records document oversight decisions, budget tracking, and confirmation that the project stays aligned with approved objectives, providing the auditor direct governance evidence.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The programmer's personal notebook</b>: is informal and not authoritative governance evidence.</span><span class='qd'><b>Vendor marketing brochures</b>: promote products and say nothing about this project's governance.</span><span class='qd'><b>The office seating chart</b>: is irrelevant to project alignment or budget.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-018","domain":3,"obj":"3A2","diff":"easy","q":"An IS auditor notes that a business case quantified benefits but omitted ongoing operating and maintenance costs. What is the MOST significant consequence?","options":["The project schedule will be shorter","User training will be unnecessary","The system will be more secure","The return on investment is overstated"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>The return on investment is overstated</strong> — leaving out recurring operating and maintenance costs understates total cost of ownership, making the ROI appear better than reality and potentially justifying an unsound investment.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The project schedule will be shorter</b>: omitting a cost category has no effect on the schedule.</span><span class='qd'><b>User training will be unnecessary</b>: training need is unrelated to whether a cost was recorded.</span><span class='qd'><b>The system will be more secure</b>: omitting costs does not affect security.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-019","domain":3,"obj":"3A3","diff":"hard","q":"An IS auditor evaluates a project that fixes cost and time but allows scope to flex to meet the deadline, delivering the highest-priority features first. Which technique is being applied?","options":["Timeboxing","Waterfall gating","Big-bang integration","Formal change freeze"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Timeboxing</strong> — timeboxing fixes the schedule and resources and adjusts scope by delivering the most important requirements within the fixed window, exactly the trade-off described.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Waterfall gating</b>: enforces sequential phase approvals and typically fixes scope, not flexes it to hit a deadline.</span><span class='qd'><b>Big-bang integration</b>: is an integration testing approach, not a scope-management technique.</span><span class='qd'><b>Formal change freeze</b>: locks scope rather than allowing it to flex.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-020","domain":3,"obj":"3A4","diff":"easy","q":"An IS auditor wants to confirm that every transaction posted to the general ledger can be traced back to its authorizing source document. Which application control provides this capability?","options":["A hash total","An audit trail (transaction log)","A screen field mask","A menu-based interface"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>An audit trail (transaction log)</strong> — a complete audit trail records each transaction with its source and processing history, enabling the auditor to trace any posted entry back to its authorizing source document.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A hash total</b>: verifies batch completeness but does not trace individual transactions to source.</span><span class='qd'><b>A screen field mask</b>: formats input display and provides no traceability.</span><span class='qd'><b>A menu-based interface</b>: aids navigation and access control, not transaction tracing.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-021","domain":3,"obj":"3B1","diff":"easy","q":"An IS auditor reviews testing artifacts. Which test is performed to verify that a newly added feature has NOT broken previously working functionality?","options":["Unit testing","Acceptance testing","Regression testing","Stress testing"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Regression testing</strong> — regression testing re-executes existing test cases after a change to confirm that previously working functionality still behaves correctly, which is exactly the stated goal.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Unit testing</b>: verifies a single new module, not the continued correctness of the whole existing system.</span><span class='qd'><b>Acceptance testing</b>: confirms the system meets user requirements, not specifically that nothing was broken.</span><span class='qd'><b>Stress testing</b>: evaluates behavior under extreme load, not functional regressions.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-022","domain":3,"obj":"3B2","diff":"hard","q":"An IS auditor examines configuration management. Which item provides the BEST assurance that the software running in production matches the approved, tested version?","options":["A configuration baseline with version identifiers compared to production","A list of open help-desk tickets","The developer's verbal confirmation","The vendor's license agreement"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>A configuration baseline with version identifiers compared to production</strong> — comparing production components against an approved, versioned baseline objectively confirms that only authorized, tested code is running, which is the essence of configuration control.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A list of open help-desk tickets</b>: reflects support issues, not which version is deployed.</span><span class='qd'><b>The developer's verbal confirmation</b>: is unverifiable and not reliable audit evidence.</span><span class='qd'><b>The vendor's license agreement</b>: governs usage rights, not the deployed version.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-023","domain":3,"obj":"3B3","diff":"easy","q":"An IS auditor is reviewing changeover options for a mission-critical system where any downtime is unacceptable and rollback must be possible. Which changeover strategy is generally the SAFEST?","options":["Direct (big-bang) cutover","Uncontrolled cutover","Parallel changeover","Deleting the legacy system before go-live"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Parallel changeover</strong> — running old and new systems simultaneously for a period provides a working fallback and lets the organization compare outputs, making it the safest option when downtime is unacceptable and rollback must remain possible.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Direct (big-bang) cutover</b>: switches entirely at once with no fallback, the riskiest choice for a critical system.</span><span class='qd'><b>Uncontrolled cutover</b>: is not a recognized controlled strategy and offers no safety.</span><span class='qd'><b>Deleting the legacy system before go-live</b>: eliminates any rollback capability and is reckless.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-024","domain":3,"obj":"3B4","diff":"easy","q":"When is a post-implementation review MOST appropriately conducted?","options":["Before the requirements are finalized","During the initial design phase","After the system has operated long enough to stabilize","Before the business case is approved"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>After the system has operated long enough to stabilize</strong> — a PIR needs a period of live operation so realized benefits, performance, and residual issues can be measured meaningfully against the original objectives.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Before the requirements are finalized</b>: there is no implemented system to review at that point.</span><span class='qd'><b>During the initial design phase</b>: nothing has been delivered to evaluate.</span><span class='qd'><b>Before the business case is approved</b>: the project has not even started, so a PIR is impossible.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-025","domain":3,"obj":"3A1","diff":"easy","q":"An IS auditor finds that a project has no formal method to measure whether it is on budget and on schedule at any point in time. Which technique should the auditor recommend to integrate cost and schedule performance?","options":["Gantt chart color coding","Increasing the project budget","Adding more developers","Earned value management"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Earned value management</strong> — EVM integrates scope, schedule, and cost by comparing the value of work performed against planned value and actual cost, giving objective indicators of budget and schedule performance at any point.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Gantt chart color coding</b>: visualizes schedule but does not quantify combined cost and schedule performance.</span><span class='qd'><b>Increasing the project budget</b>: does not measure performance and may mask problems.</span><span class='qd'><b>Adding more developers</b>: can even slow a late project and does not measure performance.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-026","domain":3,"obj":"3A2","diff":"hard","q":"An IS auditor reviews two competing project proposals. Project A returns benefits sooner but Project B returns more total benefit over a longer horizon. Which appraisal technique BEST accounts for the time value of money in comparing them?","options":["Payback period","Net present value","Simple cost total","Headcount comparison"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Net present value</strong> — NPV discounts future cash flows to present value, so it properly reflects the time value of money and allows a fair comparison of projects with different benefit timing and horizons.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Payback period</b>: measures only how fast the initial outlay is recovered and ignores the time value of money and benefits after payback.</span><span class='qd'><b>Simple cost total</b>: sums costs without discounting or considering benefits over time.</span><span class='qd'><b>Headcount comparison</b>: is irrelevant to financial appraisal of the investments.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-027","domain":3,"obj":"3A3","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor observes a development approach that builds a quick working model of the user interface, gets feedback, and refines it repeatedly to clarify requirements. Which approach is this?","options":["Waterfall","Formal V-model","Sequential batch development","Prototyping"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Prototyping</strong> — prototyping creates successive working models that users evaluate, iterating to clarify and confirm requirements, which matches the described feedback-and-refine cycle.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Waterfall</b>: fixes requirements up front and proceeds sequentially without iterative UI models.</span><span class='qd'><b>Formal V-model</b>: pairs each development stage with a corresponding test stage but is not built on iterative prototypes.</span><span class='qd'><b>Sequential batch development</b>: is not a requirements-elicitation approach and involves no iterative modeling.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-028","domain":3,"obj":"3A4","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor is testing input validation on a web form. Which check BEST prevents a user from entering an alphabetic character into a numeric quantity field?","options":["A completeness check","An output reconciliation","A field data-type (numeric) check","A retention schedule"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>A field data-type (numeric) check</strong> — a data-type or field check rejects input that does not conform to the required numeric type, directly preventing alphabetic characters in a quantity field.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A completeness check</b>: ensures required fields are present, not that a value is numeric.</span><span class='qd'><b>An output reconciliation</b>: compares totals after processing, far too late and unrelated to input type.</span><span class='qd'><b>A retention schedule</b>: governs how long data is kept, not input validity.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-029","domain":3,"obj":"3B1","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor reviews a test plan and notes that test cases were derived solely from the program's internal logic and code paths, without reference to requirements. Which testing technique is this?","options":["Black-box testing","White-box testing","Acceptance testing","Parallel testing"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>White-box testing</strong> — white-box (structural) testing designs cases from knowledge of the internal code and logic paths, aiming to exercise branches and statements, exactly as described.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Black-box testing</b>: derives cases from external requirements and behavior without knowledge of internal code.</span><span class='qd'><b>Acceptance testing</b>: validates against user requirements, not internal code paths.</span><span class='qd'><b>Parallel testing</b>: compares old and new system outputs, unrelated to code-path derivation.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-030","domain":3,"obj":"3B2","diff":"easy","q":"An IS auditor is evaluating change management. Which document provides the BEST evidence that a specific production change was properly authorized?","options":["An approved change request record","A screenshot of the developer's IDE","A vendor invoice","The system boot log"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>An approved change request record</strong> — a formal change request showing the requested change, risk assessment, and authorization signatures is direct evidence that the change was properly reviewed and approved.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A screenshot of the developer's IDE</b>: shows code but not authorization.</span><span class='qd'><b>A vendor invoice</b>: evidences a purchase, not change approval.</span><span class='qd'><b>The system boot log</b>: records startup events, not change authorization.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-031","domain":3,"obj":"3B3","diff":"hard","q":"An IS auditor reviews a plan to migrate historical data. Management proposes cleansing the legacy data before conversion. From an audit perspective, what is the MOST important control over the cleansing activity?","options":["Retaining a copy of the original data and documenting all cleansing rules","Deleting the legacy data immediately after cleansing","Letting each analyst clean data at their discretion","Skipping validation to save time"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Retaining a copy of the original data and documenting all cleansing rules</strong> — keeping the untouched source and documenting the transformation rules preserves auditability, supports reconciliation, and allows recovery if cleansing introduces errors.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Deleting the legacy data immediately after cleansing</b>: destroys the baseline needed to verify or recover from cleansing errors.</span><span class='qd'><b>Letting each analyst clean data at their discretion</b>: produces inconsistent, untraceable results.</span><span class='qd'><b>Skipping validation to save time</b>: removes the very assurance the control is meant to provide.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-032","domain":3,"obj":"3B4","diff":"medium","q":"A post-implementation review is being planned. To preserve objectivity, who should IDEALLY lead or independently participate in the review?","options":["The lead developer who wrote the code","The vendor who sold the system","The project sponsor who championed it","A party independent of the project's development and delivery"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>A party independent of the project's development and delivery</strong> — independence from those who built or promoted the system reduces bias, so an independent reviewer (such as internal audit or a neutral function) best preserves objectivity in judging outcomes.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The lead developer who wrote the code</b>: has a self-interest in a favorable outcome, impairing objectivity.</span><span class='qd'><b>The vendor who sold the system</b>: is financially motivated to report success.</span><span class='qd'><b>The project sponsor who championed it</b>: is invested in the project's perceived success and cannot be fully impartial.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-033","domain":3,"obj":"3A1","diff":"hard","q":"An IS auditor reviews estimates and finds the team used a three-point estimate (optimistic, most likely, pessimistic) for uncertain activities. Which technique is being used?","options":["PERT (Program Evaluation and Review Technique)","Function point analysis","Payback analysis","Direct cutover"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>PERT (Program Evaluation and Review Technique)</strong> — PERT computes an expected duration from optimistic, most likely, and pessimistic estimates to handle uncertainty in activity times, which is precisely the three-point method described.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Function point analysis</b>: sizes software functionality; it is not a three-point duration estimate.</span><span class='qd'><b>Payback analysis</b>: is a financial appraisal technique, not a scheduling estimate.</span><span class='qd'><b>Direct cutover</b>: is a changeover strategy, unrelated to estimation.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-034","domain":3,"obj":"3A2","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor reviews a business case and finds the benefits are described only in vague terms such as improved agility. What is the auditor's MAIN concern?","options":["The project will finish too early","Developers will have too much documentation","The system will use less storage","Benefits cannot be objectively measured or verified after implementation"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Benefits cannot be objectively measured or verified after implementation</strong> — without quantified, measurable benefit targets, the organization cannot later confirm through a post-implementation review whether the investment paid off, undermining accountability.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The project will finish too early</b>: vague benefits have no bearing on schedule.</span><span class='qd'><b>Developers will have too much documentation</b>: this is unrelated to benefit vagueness.</span><span class='qd'><b>The system will use less storage</b>: storage is irrelevant to the concern.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-035","domain":3,"obj":"3A3","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor evaluates a DevOps pipeline. Which control is MOST important to prevent insecure or unauthorized code from being automatically deployed to production?","options":["Allowing any developer to bypass the pipeline","Automated security and quality gates in the CI/CD pipeline","Manual overnight FTP uploads","Disabling all automated tests to speed delivery"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Automated security and quality gates in the CI/CD pipeline</strong> — embedding automated tests, code analysis, and approval gates ensures each build meets security and quality thresholds before automated deployment, the key control in continuous delivery.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Allowing any developer to bypass the pipeline</b>: removes the control and permits unauthorized deployments.</span><span class='qd'><b>Manual overnight FTP uploads</b>: are uncontrolled and defeat the purpose of an automated pipeline.</span><span class='qd'><b>Disabling all automated tests to speed delivery</b>: eliminates the assurance the gates provide.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-036","domain":3,"obj":"3A4","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor tests an order-entry control that rejects any order quantity greater than 10,000 units as improbable and flags it for review. Which type of edit check is this?","options":["Check digit","Limit (reasonableness) check","Sequence check","Existence check"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Limit (reasonableness) check</strong> — a limit or reasonableness check flags values that fall outside a plausible range, such as an improbably large order quantity, so the transaction can be reviewed before processing.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Check digit</b>: validates the internal structure of an identifier, not the plausibility of a quantity.</span><span class='qd'><b>Sequence check</b>: verifies ordering or numbering of records, not value plausibility.</span><span class='qd'><b>Existence check</b>: confirms a value matches a valid code in a table, not whether it is reasonable.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-037","domain":3,"obj":"3B1","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor reviews UAT sign-off and finds several high-severity defects were left open yet the system was approved for go-live. What should the auditor conclude?","options":["Open defects are normal and require no attention","UAT sign-off is irrelevant to go-live","High-severity defects improve system quality","The go-live decision may have accepted unmitigated risk without proper authorization"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>The go-live decision may have accepted unmitigated risk without proper authorization</strong> — proceeding with unresolved high-severity defects should be a formal, documented risk-acceptance decision by accountable management; its absence signals a control gap the auditor must report.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Open defects are normal and require no attention</b>: high-severity defects specifically warrant scrutiny before go-live.</span><span class='qd'><b>UAT sign-off is irrelevant to go-live</b>: UAT is a primary gate for the go-live decision.</span><span class='qd'><b>High-severity defects improve system quality</b>: defects degrade quality; the statement is false.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-038","domain":3,"obj":"3B2","diff":"hard","q":"An IS auditor reviews access rights in the software promotion process. Which segregation-of-duties arrangement is MOST appropriate?","options":["Developers should approve their own changes to production","One person should develop, test, approve, and deploy for efficiency","The person who develops code should not be the person who approves and moves it to production","Testers should also write the production code they test"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>The person who develops code should not be the person who approves and moves it to production</strong> — separating development from approval and deployment prevents a single individual from introducing and releasing unauthorized or untested changes, the core segregation-of-duties principle.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Developers should approve their own changes to production</b>: self-approval defeats independent review.</span><span class='qd'><b>One person should develop, test, approve, and deploy for efficiency</b>: concentrating all duties in one person removes all cross-checks.</span><span class='qd'><b>Testers should also write the production code they test</b>: this destroys the independence of testing.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-039","domain":3,"obj":"3B3","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor evaluates a phased changeover in which the new system is rolled out one module or location at a time. What is the PRIMARY advantage of this approach over a direct cutover?","options":["It guarantees zero cost","It removes the need for testing","It eliminates the need for user training","It reduces risk by limiting the impact of problems to a portion of the system at a time"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>It reduces risk by limiting the impact of problems to a portion of the system at a time</strong> — introducing the system incrementally contains any failure to the current module or location, allowing correction before the next phase, which lowers overall risk versus an all-at-once cutover.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>It guarantees zero cost</b>: phased changeover can actually cost more due to running interfaces between old and new.</span><span class='qd'><b>It removes the need for testing</b>: testing is still required for each phase.</span><span class='qd'><b>It eliminates the need for user training</b>: users still need training on the new system.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-040","domain":3,"obj":"3B4","diff":"easy","q":"Which of the following would an IS auditor MOST likely include in the scope of a post-implementation review?","options":["Whether the delivered system met the objectives and benefits stated in the business case","The favorite programming language of the developers","The color scheme of the login page","The brand of coffee in the break room"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Whether the delivered system met the objectives and benefits stated in the business case</strong> — a PIR assesses realized outcomes against the original objectives, benefits, costs, and lessons learned, so business-case attainment is squarely within scope.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The favorite programming language of the developers</b>: is a preference with no bearing on outcomes.</span><span class='qd'><b>The color scheme of the login page</b>: is trivial and not a benefit measure.</span><span class='qd'><b>The brand of coffee in the break room</b>: is entirely irrelevant to the review.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-041","domain":3,"obj":"3A1","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor finds that a project's scope has expanded significantly since approval, with new features added informally by users. What is the auditor's PRIMARY concern about this scope creep?","options":["Users are too involved in the project","The system will have fewer defects","Changes were made without formal change control, threatening budget, schedule, and quality","Documentation will be shorter"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Changes were made without formal change control, threatening budget, schedule, and quality</strong> — uncontrolled scope expansion bypasses impact assessment and approval, eroding the budget, timeline, and quality baselines and reducing accountability, which is the core governance risk.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Users are too involved in the project</b>: user involvement is desirable; the problem is the absence of change control, not engagement.</span><span class='qd'><b>The system will have fewer defects</b>: added, uncontrolled scope typically increases risk of defects, not reduces it.</span><span class='qd'><b>Documentation will be shorter</b>: scope creep does not shorten documentation and is irrelevant to the concern.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-042","domain":3,"obj":"3A2","diff":"easy","q":"An IS auditor is reviewing the initiation phase of a project. Which stakeholder is PRIMARILY accountable for owning the business case and securing funding for the initiative?","options":["The database administrator","The network technician","The business sponsor","The help-desk agent"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>The business sponsor</strong> — the sponsor owns the business case, champions the initiative to management, and is accountable for securing funding and ensuring the project delivers business value.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The database administrator</b>: supports data management tasks and does not own the business justification.</span><span class='qd'><b>The network technician</b>: handles infrastructure connectivity, not project funding.</span><span class='qd'><b>The help-desk agent</b>: provides user support and has no role in the business case.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-043","domain":3,"obj":"3A3","diff":"hard","q":"An IS auditor reviews a project using the spiral model. What distinguishing characteristic should the auditor expect to see documented in each cycle?","options":["A single delivery with no iteration","A formal risk analysis driving the next iteration","Complete elimination of prototyping","A fixed, unchangeable scope from the outset"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>A formal risk analysis driving the next iteration</strong> — the spiral model is risk-driven; each loop includes objective setting, a risk analysis, development, and planning for the next cycle, so risk assessment at each iteration is its defining feature.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A single delivery with no iteration</b>: the spiral model is explicitly iterative, contradicting a single delivery.</span><span class='qd'><b>Complete elimination of prototyping</b>: the spiral model often incorporates prototyping within cycles.</span><span class='qd'><b>A fixed, unchangeable scope from the outset</b>: the model expects scope and understanding to evolve across cycles.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-044","domain":3,"obj":"3A4","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor is assessing output controls for a system that generates confidential customer statements. Which control BEST ensures reports are delivered only to authorized recipients?","options":["A larger font on the report","Printing extra copies for convenience","A controlled output distribution list with recipient authentication","Storing reports on a public shared drive"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>A controlled output distribution list with recipient authentication</strong> — restricting distribution to an authorized list and authenticating recipients ensures confidential output reaches only intended parties, the essential output confidentiality control.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A larger font on the report</b>: affects readability, not who receives it.</span><span class='qd'><b>Printing extra copies for convenience</b>: increases the risk of unauthorized disclosure.</span><span class='qd'><b>Storing reports on a public shared drive</b>: exposes confidential output broadly, the opposite of a control.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-045","domain":3,"obj":"3B1","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor reviews the test environment and notes it was built with live production data containing personal information. What is the auditor's MAIN concern?","options":["Sensitive production data may be exposed to testers without adequate protection","Test results will be too accurate","The test environment will run faster","Developers will need less training"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Sensitive production data may be exposed to testers without adequate protection</strong> — using real personal data in a less-controlled test environment risks unauthorized disclosure; data should be masked or anonymized, so the exposure is the primary concern.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Test results will be too accurate</b>: accuracy is not a risk and is not why live data is problematic here.</span><span class='qd'><b>The test environment will run faster</b>: performance is unrelated to the privacy exposure.</span><span class='qd'><b>Developers will need less training</b>: training need is irrelevant to the data-exposure risk.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-046","domain":3,"obj":"3B2","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor wants to confirm that all source-code changes are tracked and that prior versions can be recovered. Which tool or control provides this?","options":["A spreadsheet of developer names","A printer queue log","A version control (source code management) system","A building access badge system"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>A version control (source code management) system</strong> — a version control system records every change with author, timestamp, and version, and allows recovery of prior versions, giving full traceability of code changes.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A spreadsheet of developer names</b>: lists people but does not track code changes or versions.</span><span class='qd'><b>A printer queue log</b>: records print jobs, not source changes.</span><span class='qd'><b>A building access badge system</b>: controls physical entry, unrelated to code versioning.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-047","domain":3,"obj":"3B3","diff":"hard","q":"An IS auditor reviews a direct (big-bang) cutover that has already been scheduled. Which contingency element is MOST important for the auditor to verify exists before approving the approach?","options":["A celebratory go-live event","A tested rollback (back-out) plan to restore the prior system","A new company logo","Additional office furniture"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>A tested rollback (back-out) plan to restore the prior system</strong> — because direct cutover has no parallel fallback, a proven back-out plan is essential so operations can be restored if the new system fails at go-live, making it the critical contingency control.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A celebratory go-live event</b>: is cosmetic and provides no recovery capability.</span><span class='qd'><b>A new company logo</b>: is irrelevant to cutover risk.</span><span class='qd'><b>Additional office furniture</b>: has nothing to do with contingency planning.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-048","domain":3,"obj":"3B4","diff":"medium","q":"During a post-implementation review, an IS auditor should place the GREATEST emphasis on which of the following?","options":["Comparing actual results and costs against the projections in the approved business case","Counting the number of lines of code written","Interviewing only the development team","Reviewing the vendor's marketing claims"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Comparing actual results and costs against the projections in the approved business case</strong> — the essence of a PIR is measuring realized benefits and costs against what was promised, so this comparison deserves the greatest emphasis.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Counting the number of lines of code written</b>: is a poor proxy for value and not a PIR objective.</span><span class='qd'><b>Interviewing only the development team</b>: yields a biased, incomplete view and omits users and sponsors.</span><span class='qd'><b>Reviewing the vendor's marketing claims</b>: reflects promotion, not actual outcomes.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-049","domain":3,"obj":"3A1","diff":"easy","q":"An IS auditor asks who is responsible for day-to-day management of project tasks, schedule, and resources. Which role is this?","options":["The steering committee chair","The internal auditor","The project manager","The end user"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>The project manager</strong> — the project manager plans, coordinates, and controls day-to-day tasks, schedule, budget, and resources to deliver the project within its constraints.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The steering committee chair</b>: provides governance and direction, not day-to-day task management.</span><span class='qd'><b>The internal auditor</b>: independently evaluates controls and should not manage the project being audited.</span><span class='qd'><b>The end user</b>: provides requirements and acceptance, not project management.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-050","domain":3,"obj":"3A2","diff":"hard","q":"An IS auditor reviews a business case that compares only the cheapest solution to doing nothing, ignoring other viable alternatives. What is the MOST significant weakness?","options":["The document is too long","The project will finish sooner","The system will be more scalable","Failure to evaluate a reasonable range of alternatives undermines the selection decision"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Failure to evaluate a reasonable range of alternatives undermines the selection decision</strong> — a sound business case weighs several viable options so management can choose the best value; considering only one alternative plus the status quo biases the decision and weakens governance.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The document is too long</b>: length is not the issue and is unrelated to alternative analysis.</span><span class='qd'><b>The project will finish sooner</b>: omitting alternatives does not affect schedule.</span><span class='qd'><b>The system will be more scalable</b>: scalability is unrelated to the absence of alternatives.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-051","domain":3,"obj":"3A3","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor evaluates a project using object-oriented development with reusable components. Which BENEFIT should the auditor recognize this approach is intended to provide?","options":["Reuse of tested components can improve reliability and reduce redundant coding","Guaranteed elimination of all defects","No need for any testing","Removal of all documentation requirements"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Reuse of tested components can improve reliability and reduce redundant coding</strong> — object orientation promotes encapsulated, reusable objects, so proven components can be reused, reducing duplicated effort and improving consistency and reliability.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Guaranteed elimination of all defects</b>: no methodology guarantees zero defects.</span><span class='qd'><b>No need for any testing</b>: reused components must still be tested in their new context.</span><span class='qd'><b>Removal of all documentation requirements</b>: documentation remains necessary for maintainability.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-052","domain":3,"obj":"3A4","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor examines a system that automatically compares the total of posted invoices with an independently maintained control total each day. Which type of control is this?","options":["A physical access control","A reconciliation control","A user training control","A screen layout control"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>A reconciliation control</strong> — comparing a processed total against an independently maintained control total to confirm agreement is a reconciliation, which detects completeness and accuracy discrepancies in processing.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A physical access control</b>: restricts entry to facilities, unrelated to comparing totals.</span><span class='qd'><b>A user training control</b>: builds user competence, not data reconciliation.</span><span class='qd'><b>A screen layout control</b>: governs interface design, not total comparison.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-053","domain":3,"obj":"3B1","diff":"easy","q":"An IS auditor reviews the sequence of testing stages. Which stage typically comes IMMEDIATELY after unit testing?","options":["Post-implementation review","Business case approval","Data archival","Integration testing"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Integration testing</strong> — after individual units are tested, integration testing verifies that the combined modules interact correctly, so it directly follows unit testing in the typical progression.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Post-implementation review</b>: occurs well after go-live, not immediately after unit testing.</span><span class='qd'><b>Business case approval</b>: happens at project initiation, before development.</span><span class='qd'><b>Data archival</b>: is an operational activity, not a testing stage that follows unit testing.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-054","domain":3,"obj":"3B2","diff":"hard","q":"An IS auditor finds that a critical application's configuration items are not formally identified or baselined. What is the MOST likely consequence the auditor should highlight?","options":["Changes cannot be reliably controlled, tracked, or rolled back","The application will run faster","The application will need no maintenance","Users will require no support"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Changes cannot be reliably controlled, tracked, or rolled back</strong> — without identified and baselined configuration items, there is no reference point to control changes, verify what is deployed, or restore a known-good state, weakening integrity and recoverability.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The application will run faster</b>: configuration management does not affect runtime speed in this way.</span><span class='qd'><b>The application will need no maintenance</b>: all applications require maintenance regardless of baselining.</span><span class='qd'><b>Users will require no support</b>: baselining has no bearing on user support needs.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-055","domain":3,"obj":"3B3","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor is reviewing a data conversion where legacy account balances must map to a new chart of accounts. Which control BEST verifies the mapping was applied correctly?","options":["Assuming the mapping is correct because the vendor said so","Deleting legacy balances before comparison","Skipping reconciliation to meet the deadline","Comparing converted balances to legacy balances using a documented mapping and reconciliation"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Comparing converted balances to legacy balances using a documented mapping and reconciliation</strong> — reconciling source and target balances against an approved mapping objectively confirms that each legacy value was translated to the correct new account, catching mapping errors.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Assuming the mapping is correct because the vendor said so</b>: relies on assertion rather than evidence.</span><span class='qd'><b>Deleting legacy balances before comparison</b>: destroys the baseline needed to verify the mapping.</span><span class='qd'><b>Skipping reconciliation to meet the deadline</b>: removes the control entirely.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-056","domain":3,"obj":"3B4","diff":"medium","q":"A post-implementation review identifies several lessons learned. What is the PRIMARY value of formally capturing these lessons?","options":["To assign blame to individuals","To improve the planning and execution of future projects","To satisfy the vendor","To lengthen the project timeline"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>To improve the planning and execution of future projects</strong> — documented lessons learned feed organizational knowledge so future projects avoid repeated mistakes and reuse what worked, which is the primary purpose of capturing them.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>To assign blame to individuals</b>: lessons learned aim at improvement, not blame.</span><span class='qd'><b>To satisfy the vendor</b>: the benefit accrues to the organization, not the vendor.</span><span class='qd'><b>To lengthen the project timeline</b>: capturing lessons does not extend the project and is not its aim.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-057","domain":3,"obj":"3A1","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor reviews resource planning and finds two critical activities were scheduled to use the same specialist at the same time. Which project management problem does this represent?","options":["A check-digit failure","A resource conflict (over-allocation)","A parallel test failure","An output distribution error"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>A resource conflict (over-allocation)</strong> — assigning the same specialist to two concurrent critical activities over-allocates that resource, threatening the schedule; recognizing this conflict is a core project-planning concern.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A check-digit failure</b>: relates to input validation, not scheduling.</span><span class='qd'><b>A parallel test failure</b>: concerns testing, not resource assignment.</span><span class='qd'><b>An output distribution error</b>: concerns report delivery, unrelated to resource scheduling.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-058","domain":3,"obj":"3A2","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor is evaluating whether a proposed solution aligns with organizational strategy. This alignment is BEST evidenced by:","options":["The number of servers to be purchased","The programming language chosen","A clear link between the project's objectives and the organization's strategic goals in the business case","The size of the project team"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>A clear link between the project's objectives and the organization's strategic goals in the business case</strong> — strategic alignment is demonstrated when the business case ties the project's objectives directly to enterprise strategy, showing it advances organizational goals.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The number of servers to be purchased</b>: is a technical detail unrelated to strategic alignment.</span><span class='qd'><b>The programming language chosen</b>: is an implementation choice, not evidence of strategy fit.</span><span class='qd'><b>The size of the project team</b>: reflects staffing, not strategic alignment.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-059","domain":3,"obj":"3A3","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor reviews an incremental (iterative) development approach. Compared with pure waterfall, what should the auditor recognize as a KEY advantage?","options":["Requirements can never change","There is no need for any planning","Testing is entirely eliminated","Usable functionality and user feedback are obtained earlier and risks surface sooner"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Usable functionality and user feedback are obtained earlier and risks surface sooner</strong> — iterative delivery produces working increments early, so users can validate them and problems are found sooner than in a single end-of-project delivery, reducing late-stage risk.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Requirements can never change</b>: iterative approaches actually accommodate change, the opposite of this claim.</span><span class='qd'><b>There is no need for any planning</b>: iterative development still requires planning per increment.</span><span class='qd'><b>Testing is entirely eliminated</b>: testing is essential in every iteration.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-060","domain":3,"obj":"3A4","diff":"hard","q":"An IS auditor is designing tests for a system's application controls. To gain the STRONGEST assurance that a programmed control works as intended in the live system, the auditor should:","options":["Read the requirements document only","Ask the developer whether the control works","Review the login banner text","Process test data (including invalid conditions) through the actual production program logic"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Process test data (including invalid conditions) through the actual production program logic</strong> — running known valid and invalid test transactions through the real program and observing whether the control accepts or rejects them provides direct, reliable evidence that the control functions as intended.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Read the requirements document only</b>: shows intent, not whether the control actually operates.</span><span class='qd'><b>Ask the developer whether the control works</b>: relies on assertion, not verification.</span><span class='qd'><b>Review the login banner text</b>: is unrelated to whether the application control functions.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-061","domain":3,"obj":"3B1","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor reviews a system test and finds it exercised the software against its specified requirements as a complete, integrated whole in an environment resembling production. Which test level is this?","options":["Unit testing","System testing","Code review","Smoke test of a single function"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>System testing</strong> — system testing evaluates the fully integrated application against its specified requirements in a production-like environment, treating the system as a whole, which matches the description.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Unit testing</b>: examines individual modules in isolation, not the integrated whole.</span><span class='qd'><b>Code review</b>: is a static inspection of source, not execution of the integrated system.</span><span class='qd'><b>Smoke test of a single function</b>: is a narrow sanity check, not full requirements-based system testing.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-062","domain":3,"obj":"3B2","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor observes that a change advisory board reviews and approves changes before they are scheduled for release. What control objective does this BEST support?","options":["Increasing the number of changes deployed","Ensuring changes are assessed for risk and impact before deployment","Reducing the need for testing","Speeding deployment by skipping approvals"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Ensuring changes are assessed for risk and impact before deployment</strong> — a change advisory board evaluates the risk, impact, and readiness of proposed changes and authorizes them, which supports controlled, low-risk deployment.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Increasing the number of changes deployed</b>: volume is not the objective of an advisory board.</span><span class='qd'><b>Reducing the need for testing</b>: the board complements testing rather than replacing it.</span><span class='qd'><b>Speeding deployment by skipping approvals</b>: contradicts the board's purpose of reviewing before release.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-063","domain":3,"obj":"3B3","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor evaluates a pilot changeover. What is the PRIMARY characteristic that distinguishes a pilot from a full parallel run?","options":["The new system is deployed to a limited group or site before wider rollout","Both systems run for the entire organization simultaneously","The legacy system is deleted immediately","No users are involved at all"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>The new system is deployed to a limited group or site before wider rollout</strong> — a pilot introduces the new system to a representative subset first to prove it in production on a small scale before expanding, which is its defining trait.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Both systems run for the entire organization simultaneously</b>: describes a full parallel run, not a pilot.</span><span class='qd'><b>The legacy system is deleted immediately</b>: no controlled changeover deletes the fallback at once.</span><span class='qd'><b>No users are involved at all</b>: a pilot specifically involves a subset of real users.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-064","domain":3,"obj":"3B4","diff":"hard","q":"Following implementation, an IS auditor finds that the system meets requirements but users have reverted to spreadsheets. During the post-implementation review, what should the auditor identify as the KEY issue?","options":["The system is technically defective","The business case had no benefits","The hardware is undersized","Low user adoption is preventing benefit realization despite a functional system"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Low user adoption is preventing benefit realization despite a functional system</strong> — a system that works but is not used cannot deliver its intended benefits; the PIR should flag adoption as the barrier and prompt investigation into training, usability, or change-management gaps.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The system is technically defective</b>: the scenario states it meets requirements, so a defect is not the issue.</span><span class='qd'><b>The business case had no benefits</b>: benefits existed; the problem is they are unrealized due to non-use.</span><span class='qd'><b>The hardware is undersized</b>: nothing indicates a capacity problem.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-065","domain":3,"obj":"3A1","diff":"easy","q":"An IS auditor reviews project documentation and wants to see how activities, their durations, and dependencies are displayed over a timeline. Which artifact provides this view?","options":["A Gantt chart","A data flow diagram","An organization chart","A network topology map"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>A Gantt chart</strong> — a Gantt chart displays project activities as bars along a timeline, showing durations and, with links, dependencies, giving a clear schedule view.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A data flow diagram</b>: shows how data moves through a system, not the project schedule.</span><span class='qd'><b>An organization chart</b>: depicts reporting relationships, not activity timelines.</span><span class='qd'><b>A network topology map</b>: shows network device layout, unrelated to scheduling.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-066","domain":3,"obj":"3A2","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor reviews a project where benefits were expected within six months but the payback period calculation shows recovery only after four years. What is the MOST appropriate auditor observation?","options":["The project must be cancelled immediately","The stated benefit timeline is inconsistent with the financial analysis and warrants clarification","Payback period is never relevant","The system will be more secure"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>The stated benefit timeline is inconsistent with the financial analysis and warrants clarification</strong> — a claimed six-month benefit against a four-year payback is a material inconsistency that the auditor should raise so management can reconcile the assumptions before relying on them.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The project must be cancelled immediately</b>: an auditor reports findings and recommends; unilateral cancellation is not the auditor's role.</span><span class='qd'><b>Payback period is never relevant</b>: payback is a legitimate, commonly used appraisal measure.</span><span class='qd'><b>The system will be more secure</b>: security is unrelated to the financial inconsistency.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-067","domain":3,"obj":"3A3","diff":"hard","q":"An IS auditor evaluates a Rapid Application Development (RAD) project. Which risk should the auditor pay the MOST attention to given RAD's emphasis on speed?","options":["The project will take too long to deliver anything","Users will be excluded from the process","Controls and documentation may be sacrificed to meet aggressive timelines","No prototypes will ever be built"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Controls and documentation may be sacrificed to meet aggressive timelines</strong> — RAD's focus on rapid delivery and prototyping can lead teams to shortcut controls, testing, and documentation, so the auditor should focus on whether adequate controls survived the speed emphasis.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The project will take too long to deliver anything</b>: RAD is designed for fast delivery, so slowness is not the characteristic risk.</span><span class='qd'><b>Users will be excluded from the process</b>: RAD relies heavily on user involvement, not exclusion.</span><span class='qd'><b>No prototypes will ever be built</b>: prototyping is central to RAD, not absent.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-068","domain":3,"obj":"3A4","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor wants to ensure that a batch of input records was completely processed with none lost. Which control is MOST directly aimed at completeness?","options":["A check digit","A record count (batch total of the number of records)","A screen color scheme","A password complexity rule"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>A record count (batch total of the number of records)</strong> — comparing the count of records submitted to the count processed directly verifies that all records were processed and none were lost or added, addressing completeness.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A check digit</b>: validates an identifier's accuracy, not batch completeness.</span><span class='qd'><b>A screen color scheme</b>: is cosmetic and irrelevant to processing completeness.</span><span class='qd'><b>A password complexity rule</b>: is an access control, not a completeness control.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-069","domain":3,"obj":"3B1","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor reviews acceptance criteria and finds they were never formally defined before UAT began. What is the MOST significant impact?","options":["There is no objective basis to decide whether the system passed acceptance","Testing will be completed faster","The system will have better performance","Documentation will be more thorough"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>There is no objective basis to decide whether the system passed acceptance</strong> — without predefined, measurable acceptance criteria, the pass/fail decision becomes subjective, so the go-live judgment lacks a defensible basis.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Testing will be completed faster</b>: undefined criteria do not legitimately speed testing and undermine its value.</span><span class='qd'><b>The system will have better performance</b>: acceptance criteria do not change runtime performance.</span><span class='qd'><b>Documentation will be more thorough</b>: the absence of criteria weakens, not strengthens, documentation.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-070","domain":3,"obj":"3B2","diff":"easy","q":"An IS auditor is verifying that only approved software versions exist in production. The BEST source of evidence is:","options":["A verbal statement from a user","The cafeteria menu","The parking lot camera footage","The release/deployment records reconciled to approved change requests"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>The release/deployment records reconciled to approved change requests</strong> — matching what was actually deployed against the corresponding approved change requests confirms that only authorized versions reached production, providing reliable evidence.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A verbal statement from a user</b>: is unverifiable and not authoritative.</span><span class='qd'><b>The cafeteria menu</b>: is entirely unrelated to software releases.</span><span class='qd'><b>The parking lot camera footage</b>: shows physical activity, not software deployment.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-071","domain":3,"obj":"3B3","diff":"hard","q":"An IS auditor reviews a completed data conversion and wants assurance that no unauthorized data was introduced during the process. Which control provides the STRONGEST such assurance?","options":["Trusting that the conversion program had no bugs","Relying on the vendor's reputation","Comparing before-and-after hash totals of key fields and investigating any discrepancy","Reviewing only a single converted record"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Comparing before-and-after hash totals of key fields and investigating any discrepancy</strong> — hash totals over source and target detect any alteration, addition, or omission of data during conversion, so reconciling them gives strong assurance of integrity.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Trusting that the conversion program had no bugs</b>: is an unverified assumption, not evidence.</span><span class='qd'><b>Relying on the vendor's reputation</b>: reputation is not a control over this specific conversion.</span><span class='qd'><b>Reviewing only a single converted record</b>: one record cannot assure integrity of the whole dataset.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-072","domain":3,"obj":"3B4","diff":"medium","q":"A post-implementation review finds the project was delivered on time and on budget, but the expected reduction in processing errors was not achieved. What should the auditor conclude about project success?","options":["The project was a complete success because it was on time","Delivery success does not equal benefit realization; the intended business outcome was not met","Benefits are irrelevant if the budget was met","The auditor should not report the shortfall"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Delivery success does not equal benefit realization; the intended business outcome was not met</strong> — being on time and on budget measures delivery, but the real test is whether promised benefits were achieved; here they were not, so the auditor should report the benefit shortfall.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The project was a complete success because it was on time</b>: ignores unrealized benefits, the core PIR measure.</span><span class='qd'><b>Benefits are irrelevant if the budget was met</b>: benefits are precisely what justify the investment.</span><span class='qd'><b>The auditor should not report the shortfall</b>: suppressing a material finding violates audit responsibilities.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-073","domain":3,"obj":"3A1","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor notes that a project has no defined milestones or phase-end deliverables against which progress is measured. What is the PRIMARY risk?","options":["The project will be completed early","Progress and problems cannot be objectively assessed until it is too late to correct them","Developers will be over-supervised","The budget will automatically shrink"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Progress and problems cannot be objectively assessed until it is too late to correct them</strong> — milestones and phase-end deliverables provide checkpoints to verify progress and catch issues early; without them, deviations go undetected until late, when correction is costly.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The project will be completed early</b>: lacking milestones does not accelerate delivery.</span><span class='qd'><b>Developers will be over-supervised</b>: the risk is too little visibility, not too much.</span><span class='qd'><b>The budget will automatically shrink</b>: milestones do not shrink budgets, and their absence does not either.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-074","domain":3,"obj":"3A2","diff":"easy","q":"An IS auditor is reviewing feasibility analysis. Which type of feasibility assesses whether the required technology and infrastructure can deliver the solution?","options":["Operational feasibility","Schedule feasibility","Technical feasibility","Cultural feasibility"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Technical feasibility</strong> — technical feasibility examines whether the necessary hardware, software, and technical capabilities exist or can be obtained to build and run the proposed solution.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Operational feasibility</b>: addresses whether the organization can operate and adopt the system, not the technology's capability.</span><span class='qd'><b>Schedule feasibility</b>: assesses whether the timeline is achievable, not technical capability.</span><span class='qd'><b>Cultural feasibility</b>: considers organizational culture fit, not technology.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-075","domain":3,"obj":"3A3","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor examines a project that outsourced development. Which control is MOST important for the auditor to verify regarding the delivered code's quality and security?","options":["The organization trusts the vendor and performs no review","Payment is released before any testing","The organization independently reviews and tests deliverables against agreed acceptance criteria","The vendor self-certifies with no evidence"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>The organization independently reviews and tests deliverables against agreed acceptance criteria</strong> — independent verification of outsourced deliverables against defined criteria ensures the client, not just the vendor, confirms quality and security before acceptance and payment.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The organization trusts the vendor and performs no review</b>: abdicates the client's control responsibility.</span><span class='qd'><b>Payment is released before any testing</b>: removes leverage and accepts unverified work.</span><span class='qd'><b>The vendor self-certifies with no evidence</b>: self-certification without evidence is not reliable assurance.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-076","domain":3,"obj":"3A4","diff":"hard","q":"An IS auditor is reviewing controls in an automated interface that transfers transactions between two systems. Which control BEST ensures that every transaction sent by the source system is received and processed by the target system exactly once?","options":["A shared login for both systems","A larger network bandwidth allocation","Interface control totals and sequence/transaction-count reconciliation between the systems","A daily reboot of both servers"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Interface control totals and sequence/transaction-count reconciliation between the systems</strong> — reconciling counts and control totals across the interface detects lost, duplicated, or out-of-order transactions, ensuring exactly-once, complete transfer between systems.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A shared login for both systems</b>: weakens accountability and does nothing for transfer completeness.</span><span class='qd'><b>A larger network bandwidth allocation</b>: improves speed but does not verify transaction delivery.</span><span class='qd'><b>A daily reboot of both servers</b>: is a maintenance action unrelated to interface integrity.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-077","domain":3,"obj":"3B1","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor reviews a test in which cases were designed only from the system's external inputs and expected outputs, with no knowledge of the internal code. Which technique is this?","options":["White-box testing","Structural path testing","Code coverage analysis","Black-box testing"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Black-box testing</strong> — black-box (functional) testing derives cases from specifications, inputs, and expected outputs without regard to internal code, exactly matching the description.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>White-box testing</b>: uses knowledge of internal code paths, the opposite of black-box.</span><span class='qd'><b>Structural path testing</b>: is a white-box technique focused on code paths.</span><span class='qd'><b>Code coverage analysis</b>: measures how much code was exercised, a white-box metric.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-078","domain":3,"obj":"3B2","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor reviews the promotion of a change and finds no evidence that it was tested before deployment to production. What is the MOST appropriate audit finding?","options":["No finding is needed because the change worked","The change should be praised for saving time","A control weakness exists because changes are deployed without evidence of testing","Testing evidence is optional for all changes"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>A control weakness exists because changes are deployed without evidence of testing</strong> — the absence of testing evidence before production deployment is a control gap regardless of the apparent outcome, and the auditor should report it.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>No finding is needed because the change worked</b>: a control gap exists even if no incident has yet occurred.</span><span class='qd'><b>The change should be praised for saving time</b>: skipping testing introduces risk, not commendation.</span><span class='qd'><b>Testing evidence is optional for all changes</b>: testing evidence is a fundamental change-management control.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-079","domain":3,"obj":"3B3","diff":"medium","q":"During deployment planning, an IS auditor asks how the organization will restore service if the new release fails immediately after go-live. Which element addresses this?","options":["A press release announcing the launch","A documented and tested back-out (rollback) procedure","A new user manual cover page","An extended lunch break for the team"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>A documented and tested back-out (rollback) procedure</strong> — a back-out procedure defines how to revert to the prior stable state if the release fails, ensuring service can be restored quickly, which directly answers the auditor's question.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A press release announcing the launch</b>: is communications, not recovery.</span><span class='qd'><b>A new user manual cover page</b>: is cosmetic and provides no recovery capability.</span><span class='qd'><b>An extended lunch break for the team</b>: has no bearing on restoring service.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-080","domain":3,"obj":"3B4","diff":"easy","q":"An IS auditor is determining the appropriate timing to schedule a post-implementation review relative to go-live. The review should occur:","options":["After a suitable stabilization period so meaningful operating data is available","Immediately at the moment of go-live","Before any code is written","Only if the project failed"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>After a suitable stabilization period so meaningful operating data is available</strong> — allowing the system to run and settle produces reliable data on performance and benefits, giving the PIR a sound basis for conclusions.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Immediately at the moment of go-live</b>: there is no operating history yet to evaluate.</span><span class='qd'><b>Before any code is written</b>: nothing has been implemented to review.</span><span class='qd'><b>Only if the project failed</b>: PIRs are valuable for successful projects too, to confirm benefits and capture lessons.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-081","domain":3,"obj":"3A1","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor evaluates a project and finds the project manager also serves as the independent quality reviewer signing off on deliverables. What principle is violated?","options":["Segregation of duties between execution and independent review","The right to a project charter","The requirement for a Gantt chart","The need for a business case"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Segregation of duties between execution and independent review</strong> — the person managing delivery cannot objectively provide independent quality assurance over their own work, so combining these roles violates segregation of duties.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The right to a project charter</b>: is not a duties-segregation principle and is unrelated.</span><span class='qd'><b>The requirement for a Gantt chart</b>: is a scheduling artifact, not a duties principle.</span><span class='qd'><b>The need for a business case</b>: concerns justification, not the conflict of roles described.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-082","domain":3,"obj":"3A2","diff":"hard","q":"An IS auditor reviews a business case and finds benefits were estimated by the same team that will build the system, with no independent challenge. What is the MOST significant risk?","options":["Optimism bias may inflate benefits, and no independent review exists to challenge the estimates","The estimates are automatically correct","The project will finish under budget","The system will require no maintenance"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Optimism bias may inflate benefits, and no independent review exists to challenge the estimates</strong> — teams invested in a project tend to overstate benefits; without independent challenge, inflated estimates can drive a poor investment decision, so this bias is the key risk.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The estimates are automatically correct</b>: self-generated estimates without challenge are especially prone to error.</span><span class='qd'><b>The project will finish under budget</b>: nothing about biased benefit estimates guarantees this.</span><span class='qd'><b>The system will require no maintenance</b>: all systems require maintenance; this is unrelated.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-083","domain":3,"obj":"3A3","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor evaluates a project that used function point analysis. What is function point analysis PRIMARILY used for?","options":["Estimating software size and effort based on the functionality delivered to the user","Encrypting production data","Approving change requests","Distributing printed reports"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Estimating software size and effort based on the functionality delivered to the user</strong> — function point analysis sizes software by counting user-facing functions (inputs, outputs, inquiries, files, interfaces), enabling effort and cost estimation independent of technology.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Encrypting production data</b>: is a security control, not an estimation technique.</span><span class='qd'><b>Approving change requests</b>: is a change-management activity, unrelated to sizing.</span><span class='qd'><b>Distributing printed reports</b>: is an output-handling task, not estimation.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-084","domain":3,"obj":"3A4","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor is reviewing controls over master file changes (for example, adding a new vendor). Which control BEST prevents fraudulent or erroneous master data?","options":["Independent authorization and review of all master file changes","Allowing any clerk to add vendors without approval","Disabling all logging of changes","Letting the requester also approve the change"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Independent authorization and review of all master file changes</strong> — requiring an independent party to authorize and review additions and edits to master data prevents a single person from inserting fraudulent or erroneous records such as fictitious vendors.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Allowing any clerk to add vendors without approval</b>: removes the control and invites fraud and error.</span><span class='qd'><b>Disabling all logging of changes</b>: eliminates the audit trail needed to detect problems.</span><span class='qd'><b>Letting the requester also approve the change</b>: violates segregation of duties.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-085","domain":3,"obj":"3B1","diff":"hard","q":"An IS auditor reviews stress and volume testing results for a new system expected to handle peak-season loads. Which conclusion would MOST concern the auditor?","options":["The system passed testing at twice the projected peak","Response times improved under load","Testing covered both average and peak volumes","The system was only tested at average load and never at projected peak volumes"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>The system was only tested at average load and never at projected peak volumes</strong> — if the system was never exercised at the peak volumes it must support, there is no assurance it will perform when it matters most, which is the auditor's primary concern.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The system passed testing at twice the projected peak</b>: exceeding the peak is reassuring, not concerning.</span><span class='qd'><b>Response times improved under load</b>: this is a positive, unexpected but not a concern.</span><span class='qd'><b>Testing covered both average and peak volumes</b>: comprehensive coverage is exactly what the auditor wants.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-086","domain":3,"obj":"3B2","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor reviews a release that bundled multiple unrelated changes together with no way to identify which change caused a subsequent failure. What release-management weakness does this illustrate?","options":["Excessive documentation of changes","Too much testing before release","Overly granular change control","Poor release packaging that hinders traceability and rollback of individual changes"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Poor release packaging that hinders traceability and rollback of individual changes</strong> — bundling unrelated changes without discrete tracking makes it impossible to isolate a fault or roll back just the offending change, undermining controllability of the release.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Excessive documentation of changes</b>: the problem is too little traceability, not too much documentation.</span><span class='qd'><b>Too much testing before release</b>: the issue is packaging, not an excess of testing.</span><span class='qd'><b>Overly granular change control</b>: the changes were bundled coarsely, the opposite of granular.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-087","domain":3,"obj":"3B3","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor reviews a data migration and finds that referential integrity between related tables was not verified after loading. What is the PRIMARY risk?","options":["Orphaned or mismatched records could corrupt business processes that rely on the relationships","The database will use less storage","Reports will render in color","Users will log in faster"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Orphaned or mismatched records could corrupt business processes that rely on the relationships</strong> — if referential integrity is not verified, child records may reference missing parents (or vice versa), producing errors and unreliable data in processes that depend on those links.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The database will use less storage</b>: integrity verification is unrelated to storage size.</span><span class='qd'><b>Reports will render in color</b>: formatting is irrelevant to data integrity.</span><span class='qd'><b>Users will log in faster</b>: login speed has nothing to do with referential integrity.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-088","domain":3,"obj":"3B4","diff":"hard","q":"A post-implementation review reveals that a control identified as necessary during design was never actually implemented in the delivered system. What should the IS auditor do?","options":["Ignore it since the system is already live","Report the missing control as a finding and assess the resulting risk exposure","Assume the developers had a good reason","Recommend removing all remaining controls"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Report the missing control as a finding and assess the resulting risk exposure</strong> — a design-mandated control that was never built is a genuine gap; the auditor's duty is to report it and evaluate the risk so management can remediate.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Ignore it since the system is already live</b>: being live does not excuse a missing control; it may increase exposure.</span><span class='qd'><b>Assume the developers had a good reason</b>: assumptions are not audit evidence and abdicate the auditor's role.</span><span class='qd'><b>Recommend removing all remaining controls</b>: reducing controls increases risk and is the opposite of sound advice.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-089","domain":3,"obj":"3A1","diff":"easy","q":"An IS auditor reviews a project and asks which document formally authorizes the project's existence and gives the project manager authority to apply resources. Which document is it?","options":["The user manual","The data dictionary","The incident report","The project charter"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>The project charter</strong> — the project charter formally authorizes the project, states its objectives, and grants the project manager the authority to apply organizational resources.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The user manual</b>: instructs end users and grants no authority.</span><span class='qd'><b>The data dictionary</b>: defines data elements, not project authorization.</span><span class='qd'><b>The incident report</b>: documents an event, not project initiation.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-090","domain":3,"obj":"3A2","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor is evaluating whether a project's benefits will be tracked after go-live. The BEST evidence that benefit realization is planned is:","options":["A benefits realization plan with defined metrics, owners, and measurement dates","A large marketing budget","A long list of project risks","A signed non-disclosure agreement"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>A benefits realization plan with defined metrics, owners, and measurement dates</strong> — a formal plan assigning measurable benefits to owners with target dates shows the organization intends to track and confirm value after implementation.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A large marketing budget</b>: spending on promotion does not evidence benefit tracking.</span><span class='qd'><b>A long list of project risks</b>: documents risks, not benefit measurement.</span><span class='qd'><b>A signed non-disclosure agreement</b>: addresses confidentiality, not benefits realization.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-091","domain":3,"obj":"3A3","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor is comparing agile and waterfall for a project with stable, well-understood requirements and strict regulatory documentation needs. Which approach is generally MORE suitable, and why?","options":["Agile, because documentation is never required","Waterfall, because stable requirements and heavy documentation fit its sequential, gated structure","Neither can ever be audited","Agile, because requirements should always change"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Waterfall, because stable requirements and heavy documentation fit its sequential, gated structure</strong> — when requirements are stable and rigorous documentation is mandated, waterfall's phase gates and comprehensive documentation align well with those needs.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Agile, because documentation is never required</b>: agile still produces documentation and the premise is false.</span><span class='qd'><b>Neither can ever be audited</b>: both methodologies are auditable.</span><span class='qd'><b>Agile, because requirements should always change</b>: the scenario states requirements are stable, so agile's change strength adds little.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-092","domain":3,"obj":"3A4","diff":"hard","q":"An IS auditor is assessing controls for a system that calculates interest. To confirm the calculation logic is correct across boundary conditions, the BEST audit technique is:","options":["Recalculating results independently for a range of test cases, including edge values, and comparing to system output","Asking the users if the numbers look about right","Reviewing the interest rate marketing brochure","Checking the color of the interest report"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Recalculating results independently for a range of test cases, including edge values, and comparing to system output</strong> — independent recalculation across normal and boundary cases directly verifies that the system's calculation logic is accurate, providing strong, objective evidence.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Asking the users if the numbers look about right</b>: is subjective and unreliable for verifying precise logic.</span><span class='qd'><b>Reviewing the interest rate marketing brochure</b>: describes products, not the calculation logic.</span><span class='qd'><b>Checking the color of the interest report</b>: is cosmetic and irrelevant to accuracy.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-093","domain":3,"obj":"3B1","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor reviews the entry criteria for user acceptance testing. Which condition is MOST appropriate to require before UAT begins?","options":["No prior testing has been performed","Developers have deployed the code straight to production","System testing is complete and known critical defects have been resolved","The business case has been discarded"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>System testing is complete and known critical defects have been resolved</strong> — UAT should start on a stable build that has passed system testing with critical defects fixed, so users evaluate a reliable system rather than rediscovering technical faults.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>No prior testing has been performed</b>: entering UAT without earlier testing wastes user effort on unstable software.</span><span class='qd'><b>Developers have deployed the code straight to production</b>: deploying before acceptance defeats the purpose of UAT.</span><span class='qd'><b>The business case has been discarded</b>: the business case remains the benchmark for acceptance.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-094","domain":3,"obj":"3B2","diff":"easy","q":"An IS auditor wants to confirm that production libraries cannot be altered by developers directly. The BEST control is:","options":["Giving all staff administrator rights","Removing all access controls","Sharing the production password widely","Restricting production library access to authorized operations staff, not developers"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Restricting production library access to authorized operations staff, not developers</strong> — limiting production library modification to a segregated, authorized group prevents developers from directly changing live code, enforcing segregation of duties.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Giving all staff administrator rights</b>: grants excessive privilege and removes the control.</span><span class='qd'><b>Removing all access controls</b>: eliminates protection entirely.</span><span class='qd'><b>Sharing the production password widely</b>: destroys accountability and access restriction.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-095","domain":3,"obj":"3B3","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor is reviewing a plan that will run the legacy and new payroll systems together for two full pay cycles and pay employees from the legacy system until results reconcile. Which changeover strategy is described?","options":["Direct cutover","Pilot at one site","Parallel changeover","Immediate legacy shutdown"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Parallel changeover</strong> — operating both systems on the same live data while continuing to rely on the proven legacy output until the new system reconciles is the defining pattern of a parallel changeover.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Direct cutover</b>: switches entirely to the new system at once with no parallel run.</span><span class='qd'><b>Pilot at one site</b>: deploys to a subset rather than running both systems for everyone.</span><span class='qd'><b>Immediate legacy shutdown</b>: contradicts continuing to pay from the legacy system.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-096","domain":3,"obj":"3B4","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor conducting a post-implementation review wants to gather balanced evidence on how well the system meets user needs. The BEST approach is to:","options":["Interview only the project sponsor","Collect input from a representative range of stakeholders, including end users, and corroborate with operating data","Rely solely on the developer's opinion","Read only the original proposal"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Collect input from a representative range of stakeholders, including end users, and corroborate with operating data</strong> — gathering views from multiple stakeholder groups and confirming them against objective operating data yields a balanced, evidence-based assessment of how well the system meets needs.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Interview only the project sponsor</b>: gives a single, potentially biased perspective.</span><span class='qd'><b>Rely solely on the developer's opinion</b>: is biased and omits the users the system serves.</span><span class='qd'><b>Read only the original proposal</b>: reflects intentions, not actual post-implementation experience.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-097","domain":3,"obj":"3A1","diff":"hard","q":"An IS auditor reviews a troubled project where the schedule is slipping. Management proposes adding many new developers late in the project to catch up. What should the auditor caution?","options":["Adding staff always guarantees the project finishes early","Communication overhead is irrelevant on software projects","Onboarding new developers takes no time","Adding staff late can further delay the project due to onboarding and communication overhead"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Adding staff late can further delay the project due to onboarding and communication overhead</strong> — piling people onto a late project increases coordination and ramp-up costs and often slows it further (Brooks's law), so the auditor should caution that this may not deliver the intended catch-up.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Adding staff always guarantees the project finishes early</b>: this is false; more people can slow a late project.</span><span class='qd'><b>Communication overhead is irrelevant on software projects</b>: coordination cost rises with team size and is very relevant.</span><span class='qd'><b>Onboarding new developers takes no time</b>: new staff need time to become productive, adding delay.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-098","domain":3,"obj":"3A4","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor tests a control that verifies a customer ID entered on a transaction actually exists in the customer master file before the transaction is accepted. Which edit check is this?","options":["A limit check","A check digit","A sequence check","An existence (validity) check"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>An existence (validity) check</strong> — an existence or validity check confirms that a coded value, such as a customer ID, matches a valid entry in a reference/master file before the transaction proceeds.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A limit check</b>: tests whether a value falls within an acceptable range, not whether it exists in a table.</span><span class='qd'><b>A check digit</b>: validates the internal arithmetic of an identifier, not its presence in a master file.</span><span class='qd'><b>A sequence check</b>: verifies ordering of records, not existence of a referenced value.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-099","domain":3,"obj":"3A3","diff":"hard","q":"An IS auditor evaluates whether an organization's SDLC includes appropriate control checkpoints. At which point should security and control requirements FIRST be formally considered?","options":["Only after the system is in production","Only during the post-implementation review","During the requirements/design phase, so controls are built in rather than added later","Never, because controls slow development"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>During the requirements/design phase, so controls are built in rather than added later</strong> — considering security and control requirements early lets them be designed into the system, which is far cheaper and more effective than retrofitting controls after build, a core secure-SDLC principle.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Only after the system is in production</b>: retrofitting controls post-production is costly and often incomplete.</span><span class='qd'><b>Only during the post-implementation review</b>: that is far too late to influence design.</span><span class='qd'><b>Never, because controls slow development</b>: omitting controls creates serious risk and is contrary to good practice.</span>"},
{"id":"D3-100","domain":3,"obj":"3B2","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor reviews the overall change and release process and wants the single BEST indicator that the process is under control. Which of the following provides it?","options":["All production changes trace to approved, tested, and documented change requests","The number of changes deployed each week is very high","Developers can deploy at any time without records","Change requests are created only after incidents occur"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>All production changes trace to approved, tested, and documented change requests</strong> — full traceability from every production change back to an authorized, tested, documented request demonstrates the process is disciplined and under control, the strongest single indicator.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The number of changes deployed each week is very high</b>: volume says nothing about control and may signal churn.</span><span class='qd'><b>Developers can deploy at any time without records</b>: describes an uncontrolled process.</span><span class='qd'><b>Change requests are created only after incidents occur</b>: reactive, after-the-fact requests indicate the process is not controlling changes in advance.</span>"}
]);
